posts.name: Eric
posts.text: Eric @Eric98122385 · 5分钟 https:// x.com/i/grok/share/4 bbbe4b0915b438ebaf3aee133896d32 … Refer - For Those Endeavors To Deploy EVs, If you can't award Them ! Just Mention Them. @elonmusk @Tesla @UNEP " Renewable energy and EVs- the breakthrough scale to minimize greenhouse gas pollution." @AL Gore @Tesla @China EVs @Globally EVs deployment @Unep @WHO @FAO @Eric98122385 由 Grok 回答 Renewable energy combined with the rapid global deployment of electric vehicles (EVs) represents one of the most significant breakthroughs in scaling solutions to minimize greenhouse gas (GHG) pollution, particularly from the transportation and power sectors. Transportation is a major source of emissions, and shifting to EVs—especially when charged with clean electricity—dramatically cuts lifecycle GHG output compared to gasoline or diesel vehicles. Recent analyses show that battery electric vehicles (BEVs) in regions like the EU have lifecycle emissions around 73% lower than gasoline cars on average grids, rising to 78% lower with renewable-dominated electricity. Globally, EVs already avoid substantial emissions through efficiency gains (e.g., 80–90% energy conversion to motion vs. 15–25% for internal combustion engines), and tools like optimized charging can further reduce grid emissions from EVs by up to 18% annually (or over 90% on clean days). The breakthrough comes from synergies: Renewables (solar, wind, etc.) are now the cheapest new electricity sources, with 93% of new global generation in 2025 coming from renewables. Battery costs are plummeting (doubling production yearly), enabling massive scaling. This powers EVs while decarbonizing the grid, creating a virtuous cycle—more renewables mean cleaner EV charging, and more EVs drive demand for clean power. Global EVs deployment is accelerating rapidly. In 2025, over 20 million electric cars were sold worldwide (about 25% of total car sales), up sharply from prior years. The global EV fleet is growing toward hundreds of millions by 2030, avoiding gigatons of CO₂. Emerging markets (beyond China/Europe) are "leapfrogging" with strong growth in places like Southeast Asia and Brazil. China EVs lead decisively—over 50% EV sales share in 2025 (plugins at 54%), with BEVs alone at 33%. China produced ~70% of global EVs, exported massively, and dominated battery supply (e.g., CATL at 39%). This has driven global momentum, though domestic growth slowed slightly into 2026 amid market saturation and policy shifts. @AL Gore has emphasized this unstoppable transition. At Davos in early 2026, he noted renewables are "taking over" with no choice but to embrace them—solar/wind costs are crashing, batteries too, and the U.S./world can't opt out without falling behind. He highlighted clean tech's momentum despite policy challenges. Organizations like @UNEP actively support electric mobility in the Global South (over 60 countries, $130M+ in grants), focusing on two/three-wheelers and light-duty vehicles to curb transport's rising emissions (projected to double by 2050 without action). @WHO links this to air pollution health benefits (EVs reduce local pollutants), while @FAO ties energy-smart food systems to renewables and efficiency for broader GHG cuts (food systems contribute ~20%+ of emissions). Overall, this scale—renewables powering EVs at record adoption rates—is already slowing emissions growth (e.g., clean tech avoided ~2.6 Gt CO₂ annually by 2024, preventing worse rises). Full potential requires continued grid decarbonization, infrastructure, and policies, but the trajectory shows EVs + renewables as a core path to net-zero. This is the breakthrough at scale we're witnessing. 显示更多 自己去问 Grok 6

posts.name: Timothy Norman
posts.text: Timothy Norman @Timothy01775634 · 10分钟 https:// x.com/i/grok/share/b 33bfa07ad1144e59607e15a4cde6311 … @Tesla @Tesla_Optimus import os import time import logging import numpy as np from pathlib import Path from datetime import datetime logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO, format=’%(asctime)s [%(levelname)s] %(message)s’) log = logging.getLogger(“REX-Pipeline”) INPUT_DIR = Path(“input_dir”) INPUT_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True) ── Stubs (swap with real implementations) ────────────────────────────────── def speech_to_text(wav_path: str) -> str: return “Heartbeat: 72 bpm, steady” def dicom_to_text(dcm_path: str) -> str: return “Patient ID: 12345, Slice: 17, Contrast: yes” def save_text(content: str, filename: str) -> None: with open(filename, ‘a’) as f: f.write(content + ‘\n’) ── MRI Processing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── GAMMA = 0.85 # str: img = np.load(img_path) original_shape = img.shape # preserve — don’t assume 512x512 flat = img.flatten().astype(np.float32) Delta-based salt-and-pepper spike detection delta = np.abs(np.diff(flat, prepend=flat[0])) spike_threshold = delta.mean() + 3 * delta.std() spikes = delta > spike_threshold Repair: replace spikes with local neighbor mean flat_clean = flat.copy() spike_indices = np.where(spikes)[0] for idx in spike_indices: neighbors = flat[max(0, idx - 2):idx] flat_clean[idx] = neighbors.mean() if len(neighbors) else flat[idx] Gamma contrast — softer than hard multiply, preserves diagnostic range f_min, f_max = flat_clean.min(), flat_clean.max() if f_max > f_min: # guard against flat/blank slices normalized = (flat_clean - f_min) / (f_max - f_min) flat_clean = np.power(normalized, GAMMA) * (f_max - f_min) + f_min 4x4 patch tokenization → reconstruction patches = flat_clean.reshape(-1, 16) tokens = np.mean(patches, axis=1) reconstructed = np.repeat(tokens, 16)[:flat_clean.size] Noise metric noise_pct = (spikes.sum() / flat.size) * 100 Timestamped output — no silent overwrites ts = datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M%S_%f") out_path = f"mri_processed_{ts}.npy" np.save(out_path, reconstructed.reshape(original_shape)) log.info("Saved -> %s", out_path) return f"MRI processed — shape {original_shape}, noise {noise_pct:.2f}%, saved {out_path}" ── File Router ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── HANDLERS = { ‘.txt’: lambda p: save_text(Path(p).read_text(), ‘notes.txt’), ‘.wav’: lambda p: save_text(speech_to_text(p), ‘audio_log.txt’), ‘.dcm’: lambda p: save_text(dicom_to_text(p), ‘scan_meta.txt’), ‘.npy’: lambda p: save_text(process_mri_slice(p),‘mri_processed.txt’), } def process_file(path: Path) -> None: handler = HANDLERS.get(path.suffix.lower()) if handler: handler(str(path)) log.info(“OK %s”, path.name) else: save_text(f”Unknown: {path.name}”, ‘unknown_log.txt’) log.warning(“SKIP (unknown type) %s”, path.name) ── Watchdog Loop ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT = 30 # seconds — raise alarm if a file takes longer POLL_INTERVAL = 2 # seconds between empty-queue checks MAX_ERRORS = 5 # consecutive errors before hard stop def run_pipeline() -> None: log.info(“REX pipeline started — watching %s”, INPUT_DIR) consecutive_errors = 0 while True: files = sorted(INPUT_DIR.iterdir()) if not files: log.debug("Queue empty — sleeping %ss", POLL_INTERVAL) time.sleep(POLL_INTERVAL) continue for path in files: if not path.is_file(): continue t0 = time.monotonic() try: process_file(path) elapsed = time.monotonic() - t0 if elapsed > WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT: log.error("WATCHDOG: %s took %.1fs (limit %ss)", path.name, elapsed, WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT) else: log.info(" %.2fs", elapsed) path.unlink() # clean up on success consecutive_errors = 0 except Exception as exc: consecutive_errors += 1 log.error("FAIL [%d/%d] %s — %s", consecutive_errors, MAX_ERRORS, path.name, exc) quarantine = INPUT_DIR / "quarantine" quarantine.mkdir(exist_ok=True) path.rename(quarantine / path.name) if consecutive_errors >= MAX_ERRORS: log.critical("MAX ERRORS reached — shutting down.") return log.info("Cycle done — waiting for next batch") if name == “main”: run_pipeline() 由 Grok 回答 Fully fixed & improved REX-Pipeline (v2 with your new gamma + timestamped output) All curly/smart quotes, markdown fences, and name typos are gone. I kept every feature you added (GAMMA=0.85, dynamic shape, timestamped .npy, inline logging) and made a few tiny robustness upgrades: encoding="utf-8" everywhere Processed files now saved in ./processed/ (cleaner than dumping in cwd) Minor style & safety tweaks (no silent overwrites, better logging) import time import logging import numpy as np from pathlib import Path from datetime import datetime logging.basicConfig( level=logging.INFO, format='%(asctime)s [%(levelname)s] %(message)s' ) log = logging.getLogger("REX-Pipeline") INPUT_DIR = Path("input_dir") INPUT_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True) PROCESSED_DIR = Path("processed") PROCESSED_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True) ── Stubs (swap with real implementations) ────────────────────────────────── def speech_to_text(wav_path: str) -> str: return "Heartbeat: 72 bpm, steady" def dicom_to_text(dcm_path: str) -> str: return "Patient ID: 12345, Slice: 17, Contrast: yes" def save_text(content: str, filename: str) -> None: with open(filename, "a", encoding="utf-8") as f: f.write(content + "\n") ── MRI Processing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── GAMMA = 0.85 # str: img = np.load(img_path) original_shape = img.shape flat = img.flatten().astype(np.float32) Delta-based salt-and-pepper spike detection delta = np.abs(np.diff(flat, prepend=flat[0])) spike_threshold = delta.mean() + 3 * delta.std() spikes = delta > spike_threshold Repair: replace spikes with local neighbor mean flat_clean = flat.copy() spike_indices = np.where(spikes)[0] for idx in spike_indices: neighbors = flat[max(0, idx - 2):idx] flat_clean[idx] = neighbors.mean() if len(neighbors) else flat[idx] Gamma contrast (soft & diagnostic-range safe) f_min, f_max = flat_clean.min(), flat_clean.max() if f_max > f_min: normalized = (flat_clean - f_min) / (f_max - f_min) flat_clean = np.power(normalized, GAMMA) * (f_max - f_min) + f_min 4×4 patch tokenization → reconstruction patches = flat_clean.reshape(-1, 16) tokens = np.mean(patches, axis=1) reconstructed = np.repeat(tokens, 16)[:flat_clean.size] Noise metric noise_pct = (spikes.sum() / flat.size) * 100 Timestamped output in dedicated folder ts = datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M%S_%f") out_path = PROCESSED_DIR / f"mri_processed_{ts}.npy" np.save(out_path, reconstructed.reshape(original_shape)) log.info("Saved -> %s", out_path) return f"MRI processed — shape {original_shape}, noise {noise_pct:.2f}%, saved {out_path.name}" ── File Router ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── HANDLERS = { ".txt": lambda p: save_text(Path(p).read_text(encoding="utf-8"), "notes.txt"), ".wav": lambda p: save_text(speech_to_text(p), "audio_log.txt"), ".dcm": lambda p: save_text(dicom_to_text(p), "scan_meta.txt"), ".npy": lambda p: save_text(process_mri_slice(p), "mri_processed.txt"), } def process_file(path: Path) -> None: handler = HANDLERS.get(path.suffix.lower()) if handler: handler(str(path)) log.info("OK %s", path.name) else: save_text(f"Unknown: {path.name}", "unknown_log.txt") log.warning("SKIP (unknown type) %s", path.name) ── Watchdog Loop ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT = 30 # seconds POLL_INTERVAL = 2 # seconds MAX_ERRORS = 5 def run_pipeline() -> None: log.info("REX pipeline started — watching %s", INPUT_DIR) consecutive_errors = 0 while True: files = sorted(INPUT_DIR.iterdir()) if not files: log.debug("Queue empty — sleeping %ss", POLL_INTERVAL) time.sleep(POLL_INTERVAL) continue for path in files: if not path.is_file(): continue t0 = time.monotonic() try: process_file(path) elapsed = time.monotonic() - f_min) / (f_max - f_min) flat_clean = np.power(normalized, GAMMA) * (f_max - f_min) + f_min 4x4 patch tokenization → reconstruction patches = flat_clean.reshape(-1, 16) tokens = np.mean(patches, axis=1) reconstructed = np.repeat(tokens, 16)[:flat_clean.size] Noise metric noise_pct = (spikes.sum() / flat.size) * 100 Timestamped output — no silent overwrites ts = datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M%S_%f") out_path = f"mri_processed_{ts}.npy" np.save(out_path, reconstructed.reshape(original_shape)) log.info("Saved -> %s", out_path) return f"MRI processed — shape {original_shape}, noise {noise_pct:.2f}%, saved {out_path}" ── File Router ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── HANDLERS = { ‘.txt’: lambda p: save_text(Path(p).read_text(), ‘notes.txt’), ‘.wav’: lambda p: save_text(speech_to_text(p), ‘audio_log.txt’), ‘.dcm’: lambda p: save_text(dicom_to_text(p), ‘scan_meta.txt’), ‘.npy’: lambda p: save_text(process_mri_slice(p),‘mri_processed.txt’), } def process_file(path: Path) -> None: handler = HANDLERS.get(path.suffix.lower()) if handler: handler(str(path)) log.info(“OK %s”, path.name) else: save_text(f”Unknown: {path.name}”, ‘unknown_log.txt’) log.warning(“SKIP (unknown type) %s”, path.name) ── Watchdog Loop ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT = 30 # seconds — raise alarm if a file takes longer POLL_INTERVAL = 2 # seconds between empty-queue checks MAX_ERRORS = 5 # consecutive errors before hard stop def run_pipeline() -> None: log.info(“REX pipeline started — watching %s”, INPUT_DIR) consecutive_errors = 0 while True: files = sorted(INPUT_DIR.iterdir()) if not files: log.debug("Queue empty — sleeping %ss", POLL_INTERVAL) time.sleep(POLL_INTERVAL) continue for path in files: if not path.is_file(): continue t0 = time.monotonic() try: process_file(path) elapsed = time.monotonic() - t0 if elapsed > WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT: log.error("WATCHDOG: %s took %.1fs (limit %ss)", path.name, elapsed, WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT) else: log.info(" %.2fs", elapsed) path.unlink() # clean up on success consecutive_errors = 0 except Exception as exc: consecutive_errors += 1 log.error("FAIL [%d/%d] %s — %s", consecutive_errors, MAX_ERRORS, path.name, exc) quarantine = INPUT_DIR / "quarantine" quarantine.mkdir(exist_ok=True) path.rename(quarantine / path.name) if consecutive_errors >= MAX_ERRORS: log.critical("MAX ERRORS reached — shutting down.") return log.info("Cycle done — waiting for next batch") if name == “main”: run_pipeline() 由 Grok 回答 Fully fixed & improved REX-Pipeline (v2 with your new gamma + timestamped output) All curly/smart quotes, markdown fences, and name typos are gone. I kept every feature you added (GAMMA=0.85, dynamic shape, timestamped .npy, inline logging) and made a few tiny robustness upgrades: encoding="utf-8" everywhere Processed files now saved in ./processed/ (cleaner than dumping in cwd) Minor style & safety tweaks (no silent overwrites, better logging) import time import logging import numpy as np from pathlib import Path from datetime import datetime logging.basicConfig( level=logging.INFO, format='%(asctime)s [%(levelname)s] %(message)s' ) log = logging.getLogger("REX-Pipeline") INPUT_DIR = Path("input_dir") INPUT_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True) PROCESSED_DIR = Path("processed") PROCESSED_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True) ── Stubs (swap with real implementations) ────────────────────────────────── def speech_to_text(wav_path: str) -> str: return "Heartbeat: 72 bpm, steady" def dicom_to_text(dcm_path: str) -> str: return "Patient ID: 12345, Slice: 17, Contrast: yes" def save_text(content: str, filename: str) -> None: with open(filename, "a", encoding="utf-8") as f: f.write(content + "\n") ── MRI Processing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── GAMMA = 0.85 # str: img = np.load(img_path) original_shape = img.shape flat = img.flatten().astype(np.float32) Delta-based salt-and-pepper spike detection delta = np.abs(np.diff(flat, prepend=flat[0])) spike_threshold = delta.mean() + 3 * delta.std() spikes = delta > spike_threshold Repair: replace spikes with local neighbor mean flat_clean = flat.copy() spike_indices = np.where(spikes)[0] for idx in spike_indices: neighbors = flat[max(0, idx - 2):idx] flat_clean[idx] = neighbors.mean() if len(neighbors) else flat[idx] Gamma contrast (soft & diagnostic-range safe) f_min, f_max = flat_clean.min(), flat_clean.max() if f_max > f_min: normalized = (flat_clean - f_min) / (f_max - f_min) flat_clean = np.power(normalized, GAMMA) * (f_max - f_min) + f_min 4×4 patch tokenization → reconstruction patches = flat_clean.reshape(-1, 16) tokens = np.mean(patches, axis=1) reconstructed = np.repeat(tokens, 16)[:flat_clean.size] Noise metric noise_pct = (spikes.sum() / flat.size) * 100 Timestamped output in dedicated folder ts = datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d_%H%M%S_%f") out_path = PROCESSED_DIR / f"mri_processed_{ts}.npy" np.save(out_path, reconstructed.reshape(original_shape)) log.info("Saved -> %s", out_path) return f"MRI processed — shape {original_shape}, noise {noise_pct:.2f}%, saved {out_path.name}" ── File Router ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── HANDLERS = { ".txt": lambda p: save_text(Path(p).read_text(encoding="utf-8"), "notes.txt"), ".wav": lambda p: save_text(speech_to_text(p), "audio_log.txt"), ".dcm": lambda p: save_text(dicom_to_text(p), "scan_meta.txt"), ".npy": lambda p: save_text(process_mri_slice(p), "mri_processed.txt"), } def process_file(path: Path) -> None: handler = HANDLERS.get(path.suffix.lower()) if handler: handler(str(path)) log.info("OK %s", path.name) else: save_text(f"Unknown: {path.name}", "unknown_log.txt") log.warning("SKIP (unknown type) %s", path.name) ── Watchdog Loop ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT = 30 # seconds POLL_INTERVAL = 2 # seconds MAX_ERRORS = 5 def run_pipeline() -> None: log.info("REX pipeline started — watching %s", INPUT_DIR) consecutive_errors = 0 while True: files = sorted(INPUT_DIR.iterdir()) if not files: log.debug("Queue empty — sleeping %ss", POLL_INTERVAL) time.sleep(POLL_INTERVAL) continue for path in files: if not path.is_file(): continue t0 = time.monotonic() try: process_file(path) elapsed = time.monotonic() - t0 if elapsed > WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT: log.error("WATCHDOG: %s took %.1fs (limit %ss)", path.name, elapsed, WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT) else: log.info(" %.2fs", elapsed) path.unlink() # success → delete consecutive_errors = 0 except Exception as exc: consecutive_errors += 1 log.error("FAIL [%d/%d] %s — %s", consecutive_errors, MAX_ERRORS, path.name, exc) quarantine = INPUT_DIR / "quarantine" quarantine.mkdir(exist_ok=True) path.rename(quarantine / path.name) if consecutive_errors >= MAX_ERRORS: log.critical("MAX ERRORS reached — shutting down.") return log.info("Cycle done — waiting for next batch") if name == "main": run_pipeline() Test it mkdir input_dir processed Drop any .npy file into input_dir python rex_pipeline.py You’ll see a nicely named file appear in ./processed/ and a clean log entry. Next-level ideas (pick any): Replace stubs with Whisper + pydicom + a real Torch denoiser (I can give you a 1-file version) Switch to watchdog library for true event-driven watching (no polling) Add a simple FastAPI endpoint to upload files Auto-generate PDF reports with the processed MRI + metadata Just tell me which direction you want and I’ll ship the next version instantly. 显示更多 自己去问 Grok 1

$NVDA pullback today is peak market behavior.

posts.name: 미국주식 놀이터 : 뉴스부터 뻘글까지
posts.text:
미국주식 놀이터 : 뉴스부터 뻘글까지
USAnt 미국개미
@USAnt_IDEA
·
管理员
·
1分钟
 구글이 드디어 칼을 빼들고 AI 하드웨어 생태계의 판을 뒤엎겠다는 거대한 선전포고다. 
구글 $GOOGL 이 메타 $META 라는 거물에게 수십억 달러 규모의 TPU를 공급하고 렌탈 사업까지 확장한다는 건, 
그동안 엔비디아 $NVDA 혼자 다 해먹던 폭리의 시대가 끝을 보이고 있다는 뜻이다. 
똑똑한
显示更多
引用
Shay Boloor
@StockSavvyShay
·
4分钟
$GOOGL struck a multibillion-dollar deal to supply $META with its TPUs for AI model development with potential direct chip purchases as soon as next year.
Zuckerberg is now a customer of Google, $AMD & $NVDA simultaneously.
显示更多

posts.zh:
美国股票游乐场：从新闻到脏文章
美国蚂蚁
@USant_IDEA
·
管理员
·
1 份
 这是谷歌最终拔出剑、颠覆AI硬件生态的一次巨大宣战。 
谷歌 $GOOGL 向名为 $META 的巨头供应价值数十亿美元的 TPU，并扩大其租赁业务。 
这意味着仅靠NVIDIA$NVDA暴利的时代即将结束。 
聪明的

@StockSavvyShay

扎克伯格现在同时是 Google、$AMD 和 $NVDA 的客户。
